---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Controls from '../components/Controls.astro';
import { site, base } from '../lib/site';
import { INSTALL } from '../data/install';

const accents = site.accents;
const haveInstall = new Set(INSTALL.map((i) => i.app));
const ports = site.ports;
const h1 = 'applications';
---
<Base
  title="enot - applications and coverage"
  desc="Every application enot ships a theme for, at which color depths, with which guarantee - generated from one spec and checked on every build."
  page="apps/">
  <div class="hero wrap">
    <h1 style={`--h1ch:${h1.length}`}>{h1}</h1>
    <div class="tail" aria-hidden="true">{accents.map((r) => <i style={`background:var(--${r})`}></i>)}</div>
    <p class="tagline">Which applications ship a theme, at which depths,
    under which guarantee.</p>
    <p class="sub">Every row comes from <code>ports/registry.json</code>,
    the manifest the build writes: a port declares its output files and
    the depth it reaches, and the regression gate checks that every color
    in those files belongs to the spec.</p>
    <Controls />
  </div>

  <section><div class="wrap">
    <h2>coverage matrix</h2>
    <p class="lead">Guarantee: <span class="badge full">full</span> carries
    the three-depth spec (true color, xterm-256, ANSI 16) with every
    invariant; <span class="badge ansi">ansi</span> addresses the terminal's
    ANSI 16 palette by index, so its guarantee is whatever terminal scheme
    supplies those 16 colors.</p>
    <div class="invwrap">
      <table class="inv">
        <tr><th>application</th><th>kind</th><th>depths</th><th>guarantee</th><th>files</th><th>install</th></tr>
        {ports.map((p) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{p.name}<br /><span style="color:var(--fg1);font-size:11px">{p.category}</span></td>
            <td>{p.kind}</td>
            <td class="num">{p.depth}</td>
            <td><span class={`badge ${p.guarantee === 'ansi' ? 'ansi' : 'full'}`}>{p.guarantee}</span></td>
            <td class="num">{p.outputs.length}</td>
            <td>{haveInstall.has(p.app) ? <a href={`${base}${p.app}/`}>{p.app}</a> : <span style="color:var(--fg1)">-</span>}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="caption">{ports.length} applications, {ports.reduce((n, p) => n + p.outputs.length, 0)} generated
    artifacts, all reproduced from <a href={`${base}colors.json`} download>colors.json</a> on every build.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section><div class="wrap">
    <h2>add a port</h2>
    <p class="lead">The engine reads one spec and renders every port
    under <code>ports/</code>; an application is added as a directory
    with a <code>port.json</code> manifest of one of three kinds.</p>
    <ol class="method">
      <li><b>template</b> - a <code>${'{'}var{'}'}</code> file rendered per
      theme, no code; covers most key=value color formats.</li>
      <li><b>module</b> - a small <code>render.py</code> for formats whose
      output needs logic (attribute handling, section inheritance).</li>
      <li><b>static</b> - a file copied verbatim, for schemes that address
      the terminal palette by index.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="lead">In all three kinds the manifest declares the output
    files, the build checks their colors against the spec, and the port
    appears in the matrix above.</p>
    <p class="caption"><a href="https://github.com/enot-theme/enot">enot-theme/enot</a>
    is the pipeline; a new port is a directory under
    <a href="https://github.com/enot-theme/enot/blob/main/ports">ports/</a>.</p>
  </div></section>

  <footer><div class="wrap">
    <span><a href={base}>&larr; enot</a> - an earthy colorscheme that survives color blindness.</span>
  </div></footer>
</Base>
